      <div class="prose">
        <h2>What this is</h2>
        <p>Connected Kerry Initiative is an independent, public-interest project that documents transport gaps across County Kerry and explores practical improvements that could make everyday travel easier.</p>
        <p>The project does not represent any political party, campaign group, or commercial interest. It does not advocate for any particular transport mode and does not take positions on contested planning or policy decisions. It aims to be a calm, factual observer of how transport works in practice in Kerry — and to make that information accessible to residents, communities, journalists, and public representatives.</p>

        <h2>Why we started it</h2>
        <p>Transport in rural Ireland is genuinely complex. Services involve multiple organisations. Responsibility is split across local and national agencies. Improvements are often announced long before they are visible on the ground. And the everyday experience of people who travel — particularly those who do not drive — is rarely captured in the way that planning data and performance statistics are.</p>
        <p>This project started from a simple observation: many transport issues in Kerry are not secret. They are just hard to see. Bus stops that exist on a database but not on a street. Routes that people walk every day but that have no infrastructure. Journeys that are difficult to describe until someone maps them. Making these things visible is a useful contribution, even before any improvement is made.</p>

        <h2>How we work</h2>
        <p>The initiative gathers evidence through direct observation, resident submissions, public data, and freedom of information requests where necessary. Evidence is verified before being published. Where something is uncertain or disputed, that uncertainty is noted explicitly.</p>
        <p>The tone of the project is deliberately constructive. Transport systems involve many people doing difficult jobs under real constraints. Pointing out gaps is not the same as blaming individuals. Progress usually requires collaboration between agencies, communities, and elected representatives — and the project aims to support that collaboration rather than replace it.</p>

        <h2>What we are not</h2>
        <p>This initiative is not a pressure group, a lobbying organisation, or a political campaign. It does not endorse candidates or parties, and it does not take positions on issues outside transport. It does not receive funding from transport operators, cycling organisations, motoring groups, or any organisation with a commercial interest in transport policy outcomes.</p>

        <div class="callout callout--green">
          <strong>Get involved</strong>
          <p>The initiative relies on observations from people who know Kerry well. If you have seen something worth documenting, or if you have a story to share, please <a href="/submit/">submit an example</a> or <a href="mailto:{{ site.site.email }}">get in touch</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

